<div id="review_652394519" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/652394519" />
    <a title="Karima" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/88244-karima"><img alt="Karima" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388625700p2/88244.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/652394519?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karima" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karima" href="/user/show/88244-karima">Karima</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer652394519" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11307406547980036566">A book to put in your treasure chest.<br/><br/>This book is based on a series of lectures (three) given at Harvard in 1983, when Welty was 74 years old. The three sections are titled: LISTENING, LEARNING TO SEE, and FINDING A VOICE. <br/>Here&apos;s a snippet from an opening paragraph:<br/><br/> When I was young enough to still spend a long time buttoning my shoes in the morning, I&apos;d listen toward the hall; Daddy upstairs <br/> was shaving in the bathroom and Mother downstairs was frying the bacon. They would begin whistling back</span>
  <span id="freeText11307406547980036566" style="display:none">A book to put in your treasure chest.<br /><br />This book is based on a series of lectures (three) given at Harvard in 1983, when Welty was 74 years old. The three sections are titled: LISTENING, LEARNING TO SEE, and FINDING A VOICE. <br />Here's a snippet from an opening paragraph:<br /><br /> When I was young enough to still spend a long time buttoning my shoes in the morning, I'd listen toward the hall; Daddy upstairs <br /> was shaving in the bathroom and Mother downstairs was frying the bacon. They would begin whistling back and forth to each <br /> other up and down the stairwell.<br /><br />Can you imagine?!?!? She had me hooked right at the get-go.<br />Nowadays, we hear of people having their house "staged" when preparing to put it on the market. The idea is that you present the house in a way in which a potential buyer can see themselves living in the house. Well, Ms Welty can "stage" a book. Though her world was about as distant from mine as the man-in-the-moon, reading this book made me WANT to be there with her, in Jackson, Mississippi (pre WW I) , while her mother read to her in a rocking chair where they shared seating, riding on the train with her father, watching the flying countryside, visiting Jackson's Carnagie Library where Mrs. Calloway, the librarian guarded the library with a dragon's eye.<br /><br /><br />I understand that there is an audio version of this book, read by the author herself. I am anxious to find it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11307406547980036566" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


